    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm working on an embedded c++ project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow memory leak. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually runs out of available ram and crashes. i don't see any obvious missing deletes in my main loop. how should i go about systematically finding where the leak is happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To identify the memory leak, you can use a tool like Valgrind (available for Linux) or AddressSanitizer (also available for Linux and Windows) with the GCC compiler. These tools can detect memory usage, identify potential leaks, and provide line numbers where the leak occurs. Additionally, use a memory profile tool like perf (Ubuntu-based Linux systems) or built-in memory monitoring tools in your IDE to track memory usage over time.",
      "source": "target",
