    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "valgrind isn't really a great option for us because our target hardware is a bare-metal environment so we don't have a full linux distro running there. we're mostly stuck with a custom RTOS. besides the big tools, what are some more manual, low-level ways to narrow it down within the code itself? specifically if i can't easily see the whole heap at once.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In a bare-metal environment, you can use manually implemented methods to track memory allocation and deallocation. One approach is to maintain a linked list of all dynamically allocated memory blocks, keeping track of allocation and deallocation events. This will require implementing memory allocation/deallocation functions that hook into your RTOS's memory management system, passing their allocations/deallocations to the tracker. This way, you can iterate over the linked list, identifying large contiguous blocks that haven't been freed, potentially indicative of a memory leak.",
